# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abstract-algebra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In mathematics, more specifically algebra, **abstract algebra** or **modern algebra** is the study of algebraic structures, which are sets with specific operations acting on their elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Algebraic structures include groups, rings, fields, modules, vector spaces, lattices, and algebras over a field.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The term *abstract algebra* was coined in the early 20th century to distinguish it from older parts of algebra, and more specifically from elementary algebra, the use of variables to represent numbers in computation and reasoning.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The abstract perspective on algebra has become so fundamental to advanced mathematics that it is simply called "algebra", while the term "abstract algebra" is seldom used except in pedagogy.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Algebraic structures, with their associated homomorphisms, form mathematical categories.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Category theory gives a unified framework to study properties and constructions that are similar for various structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Universal algebra is a related subject that studies types of algebraic structures as single objects.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For example, the structure of groups is a single object in universal algebra, which is called the *variety of groups*.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Before the nineteenth century, algebra was defined as the study of polynomials.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Abstract algebra came into existence during the nineteenth century as more complex problems and solution methods developed.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Concrete problems and examples came from number theory, geometry, analysis, and the solutions of algebraic equations.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] This unification occurred in the early decades of the 20th century and resulted in the formal axiomatic definitions of various algebraic structures such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] This historical development is almost the opposite of the treatment found in popular textbooks, such as van der Waerden's *Moderne Algebra*, which start each chapter with a formal definition of a structure and then follow it with concrete examples.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The study of polynomial equations or algebraic equations has a long history.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Circa 1700 BC, the Babylonians were able to solve quadratic equations specified as word problems.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] This word problem stage is classified as rhetorical algebra and was the dominant approach up to the 16th century.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Al-Khwarizmi originated the word "algebra" in 830 AD, but his work was entirely rhetorical algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Fully symbolic algebra did not appear until François Viète's 1591 New Algebra, and even this had some spelled out words that were given symbols in Descartes's 1637 *La Géométrie*.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The formal study of solving symbolic equations led Leonhard Euler to accept what were then considered "nonsense" roots such as negative numbers and imaginary numbers, in the late 18th century.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] However, European mathematicians, for the most part, resisted these concepts until the middle of the 19th century.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] George Peacock's 1830 *Treatise of Algebra* was the first attempt to place algebra on a strictly symbolic basis.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He distinguished a new symbolical algebra, distinct from the old arithmetical algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Whereas in arithmetical algebra $a-b$ is restricted to $a\geq b$ , in symbolical algebra all rules of operations hold with no restrictions.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Using this Peacock could show laws such as $(-a)(-b)=ab$ , by letting $d=0,c=0$ in $(d-b)(c-a)=dc+ba-ad-bc$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Peacock used what he termed the principle of the permanence of equivalent forms to justify his argument, but his reasoning suffered from the problem of induction.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For example, ${\sqrt {a}}{\sqrt {b}}={\sqrt {ab}}$ holds for the nonnegative real numbers, but not for general complex numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Several areas of mathematics led to the study of groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Lagrange's 1770 study of the solutions of the quintic equation led to the Galois group of a polynomial.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Gauss's 1801 study of Fermat's little theorem led to the ring of integers modulo n, the multiplicative group of integers modulo n, and the more general concepts of cyclic groups and abelian groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Klein's 1872 Erlangen program studied geometry and led to symmetry groups such as the Euclidean group and the group of projective transformations.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1874 Lie introduced the theory of Lie groups, aiming for "the Galois theory of differential equations".
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1876 Poincaré and Klein introduced the group of Möbius transformations, and its subgroups such as the modular group and Fuchsian group, based on work on automorphic functions in analysis.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The abstract concept of group emerged slowly over the middle of the nineteenth century.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Galois in 1832 was the first to use the term "group", signifying a collection of permutations closed under composition.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Arthur Cayley's 1854 paper *On the theory of groups* defined a group as a set with an associative composition operation and the identity 1, today called a monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1870 Kronecker defined an abstract binary operation that was closed, commutative, associative, and had the left cancellation property $b\neq c\to a\cdot b\neq a\cdot c$ , similar to the modern laws for a finite abelian group.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Weber's 1882 definition of a group was a closed binary operation that was associative and had left and right cancellation.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Walther von Dyck in 1882 was the first to require inverse elements as part of the definition of a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Once this abstract group concept emerged, results were reformulated in this abstract setting.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For example, Sylow's theorem was reproven by Frobenius in 1887 directly from the laws of a finite group, although Frobenius remarked that the theorem followed from Cauchy's theorem on permutation groups and the fact that every finite group is a subgroup of a permutation group.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Otto Hölder was particularly prolific in this area, defining quotient groups in 1889, group automorphisms in 1893, as well as simple groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He also completed the Jordan–Hölder theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Dedekind and Miller independently characterized Hamiltonian groups and introduced the notion of the commutator of two elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Burnside, Frobenius, and Molien created the representation theory of finite groups at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] A. de Séguier's 1905 monograph *Elements of the Theory of Abstract Groups* presented many of these results in an abstract, general form, relegating "concrete" groups to an appendix, although it was limited to finite groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The first monograph on both finite and infinite abstract groups was O.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Schmidt's 1916 *Abstract Theory of Groups*.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Noncommutative ring theory began with extensions of the complex numbers to hypercomplex numbers, specifically William Rowan Hamilton's quaternions in 1843.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Many other number systems followed shortly.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1844, Hamilton presented biquaternions, Cayley introduced octonions, and Grassman introduced exterior algebras.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] James Cockle presented tessarines in 1848 and coquaternions in 1849.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] William Kingdon Clifford introduced split-biquaternions in 1873.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In addition Cayley introduced group algebras over the real and complex numbers in 1854 and square matrices in two papers of 1855 and 1858.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Once there were sufficient examples, it remained to classify them.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In an 1870 monograph, Benjamin Peirce classified the more than 150 hypercomplex number systems of dimension below 6, and gave an explicit definition of an associative algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He defined nilpotent and idempotent elements and proved that any algebra contains one or the other.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He also defined the Peirce decomposition.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Frobenius in 1878 and Charles Sanders Peirce in 1881 independently proved that the only finite-dimensional division algebras over $\mathbb {R}$ were the real numbers, the complex numbers, and the quaternions.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In the 1880s Killing and Cartan showed that semisimple Lie algebras could be decomposed into simple ones, and classified all simple Lie algebras.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Cartan was the first to define concepts such as direct sum and simple algebra, and these concepts proved quite influential.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1907 Wedderburn extended Cartan's results to an arbitrary field, in what are now called the Wedderburn principal theorem and Artin–Wedderburn theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For commutative rings, several areas together led to commutative ring theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In two papers in 1828 and 1832, Gauss formulated the Gaussian integers and showed that they form a unique factorization domain (UFD) and proved the biquadratic reciprocity law.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Jacobi and Eisenstein at around the same time proved a cubic reciprocity law for the Eisenstein integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The study of Fermat's Last Theorem led to the algebraic integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1847, Gabriel Lamé thought he had proven FLT, but his proof was faulty as he assumed all the cyclotomic fields were UFDs, yet as Kummer pointed out, $\mathbb {Q} (\zeta _{23}))$ was not a UFD.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1846 and 1847 Kummer introduced ideal numbers and proved unique factorization into ideal primes for cyclotomic fields.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Dedekind extended this in 1871 to show that every nonzero ideal in the domain of integers of an algebraic number field is a unique product of prime ideals, a precursor of the theory of Dedekind domains.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Overall, Dedekind's work created the subject of algebraic number theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In the 1850s, Riemann introduced the fundamental concept of a Riemann surface.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Riemann's methods relied on an assumption he called Dirichlet's principle, which in 1870 was questioned by Weierstrass.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Much later, in 1900, Hilbert justified Riemann's approach by developing the direct method in the calculus of variations.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In the 1860s and 1870s, Clebsch, Gordan, Brill, and especially M.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Noether studied algebraic functions and curves.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In particular, Noether studied what conditions were required for a polynomial to be an element of the ideal generated by two algebraic curves in the polynomial ring $\mathbb {R} [x,y]$ , although Noether did not use this modern language.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1882 Dedekind and Weber, in analogy with Dedekind's earlier work on algebraic number theory, created a theory of algebraic function fields which allowed the first rigorous definition of a Riemann surface and a rigorous proof of the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Kronecker in the 1880s, Hilbert in 1890, Lasker in 1905, and Macaulay in 1913 further investigated the ideals of polynomial rings implicit in E.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Lasker proved a special case of the Lasker-Noether theorem, namely that every ideal in a polynomial ring is a finite intersection of primary ideals.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Macaulay proved the uniqueness of this decomposition.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Overall, this work led to the development of algebraic geometry.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1801 Gauss introduced binary quadratic forms over the integers and defined their equivalence.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He further defined the discriminant of these forms, which is an invariant of a binary form.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Between the 1860s and 1890s invariant theory developed and became a major field of algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Cayley, Sylvester, Gordan and others found the Jacobian and the Hessian for binary quartic forms and cubic forms.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1868 Gordan proved that the graded algebra of invariants of a binary form over the complex numbers was finitely generated, i.e., has a basis.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Hilbert wrote a thesis on invariants in 1885 and in 1890 showed that any form of any degree or number of variables has a basis.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He extended this further in 1890 to Hilbert's basis theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Once these theories had been developed, it was still several decades until an abstract ring concept emerged.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The first axiomatic definition was given by Abraham Fraenkel in 1914.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] His definition was mainly the standard axioms: a set with two operations addition, which forms a group (not necessarily commutative), and multiplication, which is associative, distributes over addition, and has an identity element.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In addition, he had two axioms on "regular elements" inspired by work on the p-adic numbers, which excluded now-common rings such as the ring of integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] These allowed Fraenkel to prove that addition was commutative.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Fraenkel's work aimed to transfer Steinitz's 1910 definition of fields over to rings, but it was not connected with the existing work on concrete systems.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Masazo Sono's 1917 definition was the first equivalent to the present one.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1920, Emmy Noether, in collaboration with W.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Schmeidler, published a paper about the theory of ideals in which they defined left and right ideals in a ring.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The following year she published a landmark paper called *Idealtheorie in Ringbereichen* (*Ideal theory in rings'*), analyzing ascending chain conditions with regard to (mathematical) ideals.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The publication gave rise to the term "Noetherian ring", and several other mathematical objects being called *Noetherian*.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Noted algebraist Irving Kaplansky called this work "revolutionary"; results which seemed inextricably connected to properties of polynomial rings were shown to follow from a single axiom.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Artin, inspired by Noether's work, came up with the descending chain condition.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] These definitions marked the birth of abstract ring theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1801 Gauss introduced the integers mod p, where p is a prime number.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Galois extended this in 1830 to finite fields with $p^{n}$ elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1871 Richard Dedekind introduced, for a set of real or complex numbers that is closed under the four arithmetic operations, the German word *Körper*, which means "body" or "corpus" (to suggest an organically closed entity).
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The English term "field" was introduced by Moore in 1893.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1881 Leopold Kronecker defined what he called a *domain of rationality*, which is a field of rational fractions in modern terms.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The first clear definition of an abstract field was due to Heinrich Martin Weber in 1893.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] It was missing the associative law for multiplication, but covered finite fields and the fields of algebraic number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In 1910 Steinitz synthesized the knowledge of abstract field theory accumulated so far.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] He axiomatically defined fields with the modern definition, classified them by their characteristic, and proved many theorems commonly seen today.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The end of the 19th and the beginning of the 20th century saw a change in the methodology of mathematics.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Abstract algebra emerged around the start of the 20th century, under the name *modern algebra*.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Its study was part of the drive for more intellectual rigor in mathematics.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Initially, the assumptions in classical algebra, on which the whole of mathematics (and major parts of the natural sciences) depend, took the form of axiomatic systems.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] No longer satisfied with establishing properties of concrete objects, mathematicians started to turn their attention to general theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Formal definitions of certain algebraic structures began to emerge in the 19th century.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For example, results about various groups of permutations came to be seen as instances of general theorems that concern a general notion of an *abstract group*.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Questions of structure and classification of various mathematical objects came to the forefront.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] These processes were occurring throughout all of mathematics but became especially noticeable in algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Formal definitions through primitive operations and axioms were proposed for many basic algebraic structures, such as groups, rings, and fields.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Hence such things as group theory and ring theory took their places in pure mathematics.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] By abstracting away various amounts of detail, mathematicians have defined various algebraic structures that are used in many areas of mathematics.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For instance, almost all systems studied are sets, to which the theorems of set theory apply.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Those sets that have a certain binary operation defined on them form magmas, to which the concepts concerning magmas, as well those concerning sets, apply.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] We can add additional constraints on the algebraic structure, such as associativity (to form semigroups); identity, and inverses (to form groups); and other more complex structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] With additional structure, more theorems could be proved, but the generality is reduced.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In general there is a balance between the amount of generality and the richness of the theory: more general structures have usually fewer nontrivial theorems and fewer applications.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] A group is a set G together with a "group product", a binary operation $\cdot :G\times G\rightarrow G$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] A ring is a set R with two binary operations, addition: $(x,y)\mapsto x+y,$ and multiplication: $(x,y)\mapsto xy$ satisfying the following axioms.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Because of its generality, abstract algebra is used in many fields of mathematics and science.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] For instance, algebraic topology uses algebraic objects to study topologies.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] The Poincaré conjecture, proved in 2003, asserts that the fundamental group of a manifold, which encodes information about connectedness, can be used to determine whether a manifold is a sphere or not.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Algebraic number theory studies various number rings that generalize the set of integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] Using tools of algebraic number theory, Andrew Wiles proved Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In physics, groups are used to represent symmetry operations, and the usage of group theory could simplify differential equations.
[src:abstract-algebra/abstract-algebra] In gauge theory, the requirement of local symmetry can be used to deduce the equations describing a system.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] An algebraic structure may be based on other algebraic structures with operations and axioms involving several structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For instance, a vector space involves a second structure called a field, and an operation called *scalar multiplication* between elements of the field (called *scalars*), and elements of the vector space (called *vectors*).
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Abstract algebra is the name that is commonly given to the study of algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The general theory of algebraic structures has been formalized in universal algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Category theory is another formalization that includes other mathematical structures and functions between structures of the same type (homomorphisms).
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] In universal algebra, an algebraic structure is called an *algebra*; this term may be ambiguous, since, in other contexts, an algebra is an algebraic structure that is a vector space over a field or a module over a commutative ring.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The collection of all structures of a given type (same operations and same laws) is called a variety in universal algebra; this term is also used with a completely different meaning in algebraic geometry, as an abbreviation of algebraic variety.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] In category theory, the collection of all structures of a given type and homomorphisms between them form a concrete category.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Addition and multiplication are prototypical examples of operations that combine two elements of a set to produce a third element of the same set.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] These operations obey several algebraic laws.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Many systems studied by mathematicians have operations that obey some, but not necessarily all, of the laws of ordinary arithmetic.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For example, the possible moves of an object in three-dimensional space can be combined by performing a first move of the object, and then a second move from its new position.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Such moves, formally called rigid motions, obey the associative law, but fail to satisfy the commutative law.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Sets with one or more operations that obey specific laws are called *algebraic structures*.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] When a new problem involves the same laws as such an algebraic structure, all the results that have been proved using only the laws of the structure can be directly applied to the new problem.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] In full generality, algebraic structures may involve an arbitrary collection of operations, including operations that combine more than two elements (higher arity operations) and operations that take only one argument (unary operations) or even zero arguments (nullary operations).
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The examples listed below are by no means a complete list, but include the most common structures taught in undergraduate courses.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] An axiom of an algebraic structure often has the form of an identity, that is, an equation such that the two sides of the equals sign are expressions that involve operations of the algebraic structure and variables.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] If the variables in the identity are replaced by arbitrary elements of the algebraic structure, the equality must remain true.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] , because the second operation is addition in many common examples).
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] if it is both left-distributive and right-distributive.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] is commutative, left and right distributivity are both equivalent to distributivity.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Some common axioms contain an existential clause.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] In general, such a clause can be avoided by introducing further operations, and replacing the existential clause by an identity involving the new operation.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] More precisely, let us consider an axiom of the form *"for all X there is y such that* $f(X,y)=g(X,y)$ ", where X is a k-tuple of variables.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The introduction of such auxiliary operation complicates slightly the statement of an axiom, but has some advantages.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Given a specific algebraic structure, the proof that an existential axiom is satisfied consists generally of the definition of the auxiliary function, completed with straightforward verifications.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Also, when computing in an algebraic structure, one generally uses explicitly the auxiliary operations.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Also, in universal algebra, a variety is a class of algebraic structures that share the same operations, and the same axioms, with the condition that all axioms are identities.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] What precedes shows that existential axioms of the above form are accepted in the definition of a variety.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Here are some of the most common existential axioms.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] is an algebraic structure with a binary operation that is associative, has an identity element, and for which all elements are invertible.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The axioms of an algebraic structure can be any first-order formula, that is a formula involving logical connectives (such as *"and"*, *"or"* and *"not"*), and logical quantifiers ( $\forall ,\exists$ ) that apply to elements (not to subsets) of the structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Such a typical axiom is inversion in fields.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] This axiom cannot be reduced to axioms of preceding types.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The operation inv can be viewed either as a partial operation that is not defined for *x* = 0; or as an ordinary function whose value at 0 is arbitrary and must not be used.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Algebraic structures can also coexist with added structure of non-algebraic nature, such as partial order or a topology.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The added structure must be compatible, in some sense, with the algebraic structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Algebraic structures are defined through different configurations of axioms.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Universal algebra abstractly studies such objects.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] One major dichotomy is between structures that are axiomatized entirely by *identities* and structures that are not.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] If all axioms defining a class of algebras are identities, then this class is a variety (not to be confused with algebraic varieties of algebraic geometry).
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Identities are equations formulated using only the operations the structure allows, and variables that are tacitly universally quantified over the relevant universe.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Identities contain no connectives, existentially quantified variables, or relations of any kind other than the allowed operations.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The study of varieties is an important part of universal algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] An algebraic structure in a variety may be understood as the quotient algebra of term algebra (also called "absolutely free algebra") divided by the equivalence relations generated by a set of identities.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] So, a collection of functions with given signatures generate a free algebra, the term algebra *T*.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Given a set of equational identities (the axioms), one may consider their symmetric, transitive closure *E*.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] The quotient algebra *T*/*E* is then the algebraic structure or variety.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Thus, for example, groups have a signature containing two operators: the multiplication operator *m*, taking two arguments, and the inverse operator *i*, taking one argument, and the identity element *e*, a constant, which may be considered an operator that takes zero arguments.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Given a (countable) set of variables *x*, *y*, *z*, etc. the term algebra is the collection of all possible terms involving *m*, *i*, *e* and the variables; so for example, *m*(*i*(*x*), *m*(*x*, *m*(*y*,*e*))) would be an element of the term algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] These equations induce equivalence classes on the free algebra; the quotient algebra then has the algebraic structure of a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Structures such as fields have some axioms that hold only for nonzero members of *S*.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For an algebraic structure to be a variety, its operations must be defined for *all* members of *S*; there can be no partial operations.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Structures whose axioms unavoidably include nonidentities are among the most important ones in mathematics, e.g., fields and division rings.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Structures with nonidentities present challenges that varieties do not.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For example, the direct product of two fields is not a field, because $(1,0)\cdot (0,1)=(0,0)$ , but fields do not have zero divisors.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Category theory is another tool for studying algebraic structures (see, for example, Mac Lane 1998).
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] A category is a collection of *objects* with associated *morphisms.* Every algebraic structure has its own notion of homomorphism, namely any function compatible with the operation(s) defining the structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] In this way, every algebraic structure gives rise to a category.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For example, the category of groups has all groups as objects and all group homomorphisms as morphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] This concrete category may be seen as a category of sets with added category-theoretic structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] Likewise, the category of topological groups (whose morphisms are the continuous group homomorphisms) is a category of topological spaces with extra structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] A forgetful functor between categories of algebraic structures "forgets" a part of a structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] In a slight abuse of notation, the word "structure" can also refer to just the operations on a structure, instead of the underlying set itself.
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For example, the sentence, "We have defined a ring *structure* on the set A ", means that we have defined ring *operations* on the set A .
[src:abstract-algebra/algebraic-structure] For another example, the group $(\mathbb {Z} ,+)$ can be seen as a set $\mathbb {Z}$ that is equipped with an *algebraic structure,* namely the *operation* + .
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In mathematics, **Galois theory**, originally introduced by Évariste Galois, provides a connection between field theory and group theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This connection, the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, allows reducing certain problems in field theory to group theory, which makes them simpler and easier to understand.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois introduced the subject for studying roots of polynomials.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This widely generalizes the Abel–Ruffini theorem, which asserts that a general polynomial of degree at least five cannot be solved by radicals.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois' work was published by Joseph Liouville fourteen years after his death.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The theory took longer to become popular among mathematicians and to be well understood.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois theory has been generalized to Galois connections and Grothendieck's Galois theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The Abel–Ruffini theorem provides a counterexample proving that there are polynomial equations for which such a formula cannot exist.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois' theory provides a much more complete answer to this question, by explaining why it *is* possible to solve some equations, including all those of degree four or lower, in the above manner, and why it is not possible for most equations of degree five or higher.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Furthermore, it provides a means of determining whether a particular equation can be solved that is both conceptually clear and easily expressed as an algorithm.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois' theory also gives a clear insight into questions concerning problems in compass and straightedge construction.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] It gives an elegant characterization of the ratios of lengths that can be constructed with this method.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Why is it not possible to trisect every angle using a compass and a straightedge?
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Why is doubling the cube not possible with the same method?
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois' theory originated in the study of symmetric functions – the coefficients of a monic polynomial are (up to sign) the elementary symmetric polynomials in the roots.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This was first formalized by the 16th-century French mathematician François Viète, in Viète's formulas, for the case of positive real roots.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] See Discriminant § Low degrees for details.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The cubic was first partly solved by the 15–16th-century Italian mathematician Scipione del Ferro, who did not however publish his results; this method, though, only solved one type of cubic equation.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This solution was then rediscovered independently in 1535 by Niccolò Fontana Tartaglia, who shared it with Gerolamo Cardano, asking him to not publish it.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Cardano then extended this to numerous other cases, using similar arguments; see more details at Cardano's method.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] With the benefit of modern notation and complex numbers, the formulae in this book do work in the general case, but Cardano did not know this.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] It was Rafael Bombelli who managed to understand how to work with complex numbers in order to solve all forms of cubic equation.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Crucially, however, he did not consider *composition* of permutations.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Lagrange's method did not extend to quintic equations or higher, because the resolvent had higher degree.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The quintic was almost proven to have no general solutions by radicals by Paolo Ruffini in 1799, whose key insight was to use permutation *groups*, not just a single permutation.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] His solution contained a gap, which Cauchy considered minor, though this was not patched until the work of the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel, who published a proof in 1824, thus establishing the Abel–Ruffini theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This group was always solvable for polynomials of degree four or less, but not always so for polynomials of degree five and greater, which explains why there is no general solution in higher degrees.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In 1830 Galois (at the age of 18) submitted to the French Academy of Sciences a memoir on his theory of solvability by radicals; Galois' paper was ultimately rejected in 1831 as being too sketchy and for giving a condition in terms of the roots of the equation instead of its coefficients.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois then died in a duel in 1832, and his paper, "*Mémoire sur les conditions de résolubilité des équations par radicaux*", remained unpublished until 1846 when it was published by Joseph Liouville accompanied by some of his own explanations.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Prior to this publication, Liouville announced Galois' result to the Academy of Sciences in a speech he gave on 4 July 1843.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois' theory was notoriously difficult for his contemporaries to understand, especially to the level where they could expand on it.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] For example, in his 1846 commentary, Liouville completely missed the group-theoretic core of Galois' method.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Joseph Alfred Serret who attended some of Liouville's talks, included Galois' theory in his 1866 (third edition) of his textbook *Cours d'algèbre supérieure*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Serret's pupil, Camille Jordan, had an even better understanding reflected in his 1870 book *Traité des substitutions et des équations algébriques*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Outside France, Galois' theory remained more obscure for a longer period.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In Britain, Cayley failed to grasp its depth and popular British algebra textbooks did not even mention Galois' theory until well after the turn of the century.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In Germany, Kronecker's writings focused more on Abel's result.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Dedekind wrote little about Galois' theory, but lectured on it at Göttingen in 1858, showing a very good understanding.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Eugen Netto's books of the 1880s, based on Jordan's *Traité*, made Galois theory accessible to a wider German and American audience as did Heinrich Martin Weber's 1895 algebra textbook.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Given a polynomial, it may be that some of the roots are connected by various algebraic equations.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] For example, it may be that for two of the roots, say *A* and *B*, that *A*2 + 5*B*3 = 7.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The central idea of Galois' theory is to consider permutations (or rearrangements) of the roots such that *any* algebraic equation satisfied by the roots is *still satisfied* after the roots have been permuted.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Originally, the theory had been developed for algebraic equations whose coefficients are rational numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] It extends naturally to equations with coefficients in any field, but this will not be considered in the simple examples below.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] These permutations together form a permutation group, also called the Galois group of the polynomial, which is explicitly described in the following examples.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] If we exchange *A* and *B* in either of the last two equations we obtain another true statement.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] For example, the equation *A* + *B* = 4 becomes *B* + *A* = 4.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] It is more generally true that this holds for *every* possible algebraic relation between *A* and *B* such that all coefficients are rational; that is, in any such relation, swapping *A* and *B* yields another true relation.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This results from the theory of symmetric polynomials, which, in this case, may be replaced by formula manipulations involving the binomial theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] One might object that *A* and *B* are related by the algebraic equation *A* − *B* − 2√3 = 0, which does not remain true when *A* and *B* are exchanged.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] However, this relation is not considered here, because it has the coefficient −2√3 which is not rational.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] We conclude that the Galois group of the polynomial *x*2 − 4*x* + 1 consists of two permutations: the identity permutation which leaves *A* and *B* untouched, and the transposition permutation which exchanges *A* and *B*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] As all groups with two elements are isomorphic, this Galois group is isomorphic to the multiplicative group {1, −1}.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] A similar discussion applies to any quadratic polynomial *ax*2 + *bx* + *c*, where *a*, *b* and *c* are rational numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Among the 24 possible permutations of these four roots, four are particularly simple, those consisting in the sign change of 0, 1, or 2 square roots.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] They form a group that is isomorphic to the Klein four-group.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Galois theory implies that, since the polynomial is irreducible, the Galois group has at least four elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] For proving that the Galois group consists of these four permutations, it suffices thus to show that every element of the Galois group is determined by the image of A, which can be shown as follows.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The members of the Galois group must preserve any algebraic equation with rational coefficients involving *A*, *B*, *C* and *D*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This implies that the Galois group is isomorphic to the Klein four-group.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In the modern approach, one starts with a field extension *L*/*K* (read "*L* over *K*"), and examines the group of automorphisms of *L* that fix *K*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] See the article on Galois groups for further explanation and examples.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The connection between the two approaches is as follows.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The coefficients of the polynomial in question should be chosen from the base field *K*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The top field *L* should be the field obtained by adjoining the roots of the polynomial in question to the base field *K*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Any permutation of the roots which respects algebraic equations as described above gives rise to an automorphism of *L*/*K*, and vice versa.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In the first example above, we were studying the extension **Q**(√3)/**Q**, where **Q** is the field of rational numbers, and **Q**(√3) is the field obtained from **Q** by adjoining √3.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] There are several advantages to the modern approach over the permutation group approach.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The notion of a solvable group in group theory allows one to determine whether a polynomial is solvable in radicals, depending on whether its Galois group has the property of solvability.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In essence, each field extension *L*/*K* corresponds to a factor group in a composition series of the Galois group.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] If all the factor groups in its composition series are cyclic, the Galois group is called *solvable*, and all of the elements of the corresponding field can be found by repeatedly taking roots, products, and sums of elements from the base field (usually **Q**).
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The Abel–Ruffini theorem results from the fact that for *n* > 4 the symmetric group *S**n* contains a simple, noncyclic, normal subgroup, namely the alternating group *A**n*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Van der Waerden cites the polynomial *f*(*x*) = *x*5 − *x* − 1.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] By the rational root theorem, this has no rational zeroes.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Neither does it have linear factors modulo 2 or 3.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The Galois group of *f*(*x*) modulo 2 is cyclic of order 6, because *f*(*x*) modulo 2 factors into polynomials of orders 2 and 3, (*x*2 + *x* + 1)(*x*3 + *x*2 + 1).
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] It is known that a Galois group modulo a prime is isomorphic to a subgroup of the Galois group over the rationals.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] A permutation group on 5 objects with elements of orders 6 and 5 must be the symmetric group *S*5, which is therefore the Galois group of *f*(*x*).
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] This is one of the simplest examples of a non-solvable quintic polynomial.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] According to Serge Lang, Emil Artin was fond of this example.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The *inverse Galois problem* is to find a field extension with a given Galois group.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] As long as one does not also specify the ground field, the problem is not very difficult, and all finite groups do occur as Galois groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] For showing this, one may proceed as follows.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Choose a field *K* and a finite group *G*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Cayley's theorem says that *G* is (up to isomorphism) a subgroup of the symmetric group *S* on the elements of *G*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Choose indeterminates {*x**α*}, one for each element *α* of *G*, and adjoin them to *K* to get the field *F* = *K*({*x**α*}).
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Contained within *F* is the field *L* of symmetric rational functions in the {*x**α*}.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The Galois group of *F*/*L* is *S*, by a basic result of Emil Artin.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] *G* acts on *F* by restriction of action of *S*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] If the fixed field of this action is *M*, then, by the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, the Galois group of *F*/*M* is *G*.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] On the other hand, it is an open problem whether every finite group is the Galois group of a field extension of the field **Q** of the rational numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Igor Shafarevich proved that every solvable finite group is the Galois group of some extension of **Q**.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Various people have solved the inverse Galois problem for selected non-Abelian simple groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Existence of solutions has been shown for all but possibly one (Mathieu group *M*23) of the 26 sporadic simple groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] There is even a polynomial with integral coefficients whose Galois group is the Monster group.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In the form mentioned above, including in particular the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, the theory only considers Galois extensions, which are in particular separable.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] General field extensions can be split into a separable, followed by a purely inseparable field extension.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] For a purely inseparable extension *F* / *K*, there is a Galois theory where the Galois group is replaced by the vector space of derivations, $Der_{K}(F,F)$ , i.e., *K*-linear endomorphisms of *F* satisfying the Leibniz rule.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] In this correspondence, an intermediate field *E* is assigned $Der_{E}(F,F)\subset Der_{K}(F,F)$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Conversely, a subspace $V\subset Der_{K}(F,F)$ satisfying appropriate further conditions is mapped to $\{x\in F,f(x)=0\ \forall f\in V\}$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] Under the assumption $F^{p}\subset K$ , Jacobson (1944) showed that this establishes a one-to-one correspondence.
[src:abstract-algebra/galois-theory] The condition imposed by Jacobson has been removed by Brantner & Waldron (2020), by giving a correspondence using notions of derived algebraic geometry.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In algebra, a **homomorphism** is a structure-preserving map between two algebraic structures of the same type (such as two groups, two rings, or two vector spaces).
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The word *homomorphism* comes from the Ancient Greek language: ὁμός (*homos*) meaning "same" and μορφή (*morphe*) meaning "form" or "shape".
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] However, the word was apparently introduced to mathematics due to a (mis)translation of German *ähnlich* meaning "similar" to ὁμός meaning "same".
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The term "homomorphism" appeared as early as 1892, when it was attributed to the German mathematician Felix Klein (1849–1925).
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Homomorphisms of vector spaces are also called linear maps, and their study is the subject of linear algebra.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The concept of homomorphism has been generalized, under the name of morphism, to many other structures that either do not have an underlying set, or are not algebraic.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] This generalization is the starting point of category theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A homomorphism may also be an isomorphism, an endomorphism, an automorphism, etc.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Each of those can be defined in a way that may be generalized to any class of morphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A homomorphism is a map between two algebraic structures of the same type (e.g. two groups, two fields, two vector spaces), that preserves the operations of the structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] One says often that f preserves the operation or is compatible with the operation.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The operations that must be preserved by a homomorphism include 0-ary operations, that is the constants.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In particular, when an identity element is required by the type of structure, the identity element of the first structure must be mapped to the corresponding identity element of the second structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] An algebraic structure may have more than one operation, and a homomorphism is required to preserve each operation.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Thus a map that preserves only some of the operations is not a homomorphism of the structure, but only a homomorphism of the substructure obtained by considering only the preserved operations.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For example, a map between monoids that preserves the monoid operation and not the identity element, is not a monoid homomorphism, but only a semigroup homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The notation for the operations does not need to be the same in the source and the target of a homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For example, the real numbers form a group for addition, and the positive real numbers form a group for multiplication.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] and is thus a homomorphism between these two groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] $\ln(xy)=\ln(x)+\ln(y),$ and is also a group homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The real numbers are a ring, having both addition and multiplication.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The set of all 2×2 matrices is also a ring, under matrix addition and matrix multiplication.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For another example, the nonzero complex numbers form a group under the operation of multiplication, as do the nonzero real numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] That is, f is the absolute value (or modulus) of the complex number z .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] As another example, the diagram shows a monoid homomorphism f from the monoid $(\mathbb {N} ,+,0)$ to the monoid $(\mathbb {N} ,\times ,1)$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Due to the different names of corresponding operations, the structure preservation properties satisfied by f amount to $f(x+y)=f(x)\times f(y)$ and $f(0)=1$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A composition algebra A over a field F has a quadratic form, called a *norm*, $N:A\to F$ , which is a group homomorphism from the multiplicative group of A to the multiplicative group of F .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Several kinds of homomorphisms have a specific name, which is also defined for general morphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] An isomorphism between algebraic structures of the same type is commonly defined as a bijective homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In the more general context of category theory, an isomorphism is defined as a morphism that has an inverse that is also a morphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In the specific case of algebraic structures, the two definitions are equivalent, although they may differ for non-algebraic structures, which have an underlying set.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] If A and B have underlying sets, and $f:A\to B$ has an inverse g , then f is bijective.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In fact, f is injective, as $f(x)=f(y)$ implies $x=g(f(x))=g(f(y))=y$ , and f is surjective, as, for any x in B , one has $x=f(g(x))$ , and x is the image of an element of A .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Conversely, if $f:A\to B$ is a bijective homomorphism between algebraic structures, let $g:B\to A$ be the map such that $g(y)$ is the unique element x of A such that $f(x)=y$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] One has $f\circ g=\operatorname {Id} _{B}{\text{ and }}g\circ f=\operatorname {Id} _{A},$ and it remains only to show that *g* is a homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] and g is thus compatible with $*.$ As the proof is similar for any arity, this shows that g is a homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] This proof does not work for non-algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For example, for topological spaces, a morphism is a continuous map, and the inverse of a bijective continuous map is not necessarily continuous.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] An isomorphism of topological spaces, called homeomorphism or bicontinuous map, is thus a bijective continuous map, whose inverse is also continuous.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] An endomorphism is a homomorphism whose domain equals the codomain, or, more generally, a morphism whose source is equal to its target.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The endomorphisms of an algebraic structure, or of an object of a category, form a monoid under composition.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The endomorphisms of a vector space or of a module form a ring.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In the case of a vector space or a free module of finite dimension, the choice of a basis induces a ring isomorphism between the ring of endomorphisms and the ring of square matrices of the same dimension.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] An automorphism is an endomorphism that is also an isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The automorphisms of an algebraic structure or of an object of a category form a group under composition, which is called the automorphism group of the structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Many groups that have received a name are automorphism groups of some algebraic structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For example, the general linear group $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(k)$ is the automorphism group of a vector space of dimension n over a field k .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The automorphism groups of fields were introduced by Évariste Galois for studying the roots of polynomials, and are the basis of Galois theory.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For algebraic structures, monomorphisms are commonly defined as injective homomorphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In the more general context of category theory, a monomorphism is defined as a morphism that is **left cancelable**.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] This means that a (homo)morphism $f:A\to B$ is a monomorphism if, for any pair g , h of morphisms from any other object C to A , then $f\circ g=f\circ h$ implies $g=h$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] These two definitions of *monomorphism* are equivalent for all common algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In particular, the two definitions of a monomorphism are equivalent for sets, magmas, semigroups, monoids, groups, rings, fields, vector spaces and modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A **split monomorphism** is a homomorphism that has a left inverse and thus it is itself a right inverse of that other homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] That is, a homomorphism $f\colon A\to B$ is a split monomorphism if there exists a homomorphism $g\colon B\to A$ such that $g\circ f=\operatorname {Id} _{A}.$ A split monomorphism is always a monomorphism, for both meanings of *monomorphism*.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For sets and vector spaces, every monomorphism is a split monomorphism, but this property does not hold for most common algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In algebra, **epimorphisms** are often defined as surjective homomorphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] On the other hand, in category theory, epimorphisms are defined as **right cancelable** morphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] This means that a (homo)morphism $f:A\to B$ is an epimorphism if, for any pair g , h of morphisms from B to any other object C , the equality $g\circ f=h\circ f$ implies $g=h$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A surjective homomorphism is always right cancelable, but the converse is not always true for algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] However, the two definitions of *epimorphism* are equivalent for sets, vector spaces, abelian groups, modules (see below for a proof), and groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The importance of these structures in all mathematics, especially in linear algebra and homological algebra, may explain the coexistence of two non-equivalent definitions.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Algebraic structures for which there exist non-surjective epimorphisms include semigroups and rings.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The most basic example is the inclusion of integers into rational numbers, which is a homomorphism of rings and of multiplicative semigroups.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For both structures it is a monomorphism and a non-surjective epimorphism, but not an isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A wide generalization of this example is the localization of a ring by a multiplicative set.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Every localization is a ring epimorphism, which is not, in general, surjective.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] As localizations are fundamental in commutative algebra and algebraic geometry, this may explain why in these areas, the definition of epimorphisms as right cancelable homomorphisms is generally preferred.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] A **split epimorphism** is a homomorphism that has a right inverse and thus it is itself a left inverse of that other homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] That is, a homomorphism $f\colon A\to B$ is a split epimorphism if there exists a homomorphism $g\colon B\to A$ such that $f\circ g=\operatorname {Id} _{B}.$ A split epimorphism is always an epimorphism, for both meanings of *epimorphism*.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] For sets and vector spaces, every epimorphism is a split epimorphism, but this property does not hold for most common algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] the last implication is an equivalence for sets, vector spaces, modules, abelian groups, and groups; the first implication is an equivalence for sets and vector spaces.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Any homomorphism $f:X\to Y$ defines an equivalence relation $\sim$ on X by $a\sim b$ if and only if $f(a)=f(b)$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The relation $\sim$ is called the **kernel** of f .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The quotient set $X/{\sim }$ can then be given a structure of the same type as X , in a natural way, by defining the operations of the quotient set by $[x]\ast [y]=[x\ast y]$ , for each operation $\ast$ of X .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In that case the image of X in Y under the homomorphism f is necessarily isomorphic to $X/\!\sim$ ; this fact is one of the isomorphism theorems.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] When the algebraic structure is a group for some operation, the equivalence class K of the identity element of this operation suffices to characterize the equivalence relation.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In this case, the quotient by the equivalence relation is denoted by $X/K$ (usually read as " X mod K ").
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Also in this case, it is K , rather than $\sim$ , that is called the kernel of f .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The kernels of homomorphisms of a given type of algebraic structure are naturally equipped with some structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In model theory, the notion of an algebraic structure is generalized to structures involving both operations and relations.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Let *L* be a signature consisting of function and relation symbols, and *A*, *B* be two *L*-structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] In the special case with just one binary relation, we obtain the notion of a graph homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Homomorphisms are also used in the study of formal languages and are often briefly referred to as *morphisms*.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] If h is a homomorphism on $\Sigma _{1}^{*}$ and $\varepsilon$ denotes the empty string, then h is called an $\varepsilon$ *-free homomorphism* when $h(x)\neq \varepsilon$ for all $x\neq \varepsilon$ in $\Sigma _{1}^{*}$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] If $|h(a)|=1$ for all $a\in \Sigma _{1}$ (that is, h is 1-uniform), then h is also called a *coding* or a *projection*.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] The set $\Sigma ^{*}$ of words formed from the alphabet $\Sigma$ may be thought of as the free monoid generated by $\Sigma$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] Here the monoid operation is concatenation and the identity element is the empty word.
[src:abstract-algebra/homomorphism] From this perspective, a language homomorphism is precisely a monoid homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] under multiplication is isomorphic to the group of rotations of the regular pentagon under composition.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In mathematics, an **isomorphism** is a structure-preserving mapping or morphism between two structures of the same type that can be reversed by an inverse mapping.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Two mathematical structures are **isomorphic** if an isomorphism exists between them, and this is often denoted as ⁠ $A\cong B$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The word is derived from Ancient Greek ἴσος*(*isos*)* 'equal' and μορφή*(*morphe*)* 'form, shape'.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The interest in isomorphisms lies in the fact that two isomorphic objects have the same properties (excluding further information such as additional structure or names of objects).
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Thus isomorphic structures cannot be distinguished from the point of view of structure only, and may often be identified.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In mathematical jargon, one says that two objects are the same up to an isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] A common example where isomorphic structures cannot be identified is when the structures are substructures of a larger one.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] For example, all subspaces of dimension one of a vector space are isomorphic and cannot be identified.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] An automorphism is an isomorphism from a structure to itself.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] For example, for every prime number p, all fields with p elements are canonically isomorphic, with a unique isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The isomorphism theorems provide canonical isomorphisms that are not unique.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The term *isomorphism* is mainly used for algebraic structures and categories.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In the case of algebraic structures, mappings are called homomorphisms, and a homomorphism is an isomorphism if and only if it is bijective.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In various areas of mathematics, isomorphisms have received specialized names, depending on the type of structure under consideration.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Category theory, which can be viewed as a formalization of the concept of mapping between structures, provides a language that may be used to unify the approach to these different aspects of the basic idea.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Let $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ be the multiplicative group of positive real numbers, and let $\mathbb {R}$ be the additive group of real numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The logarithm function $\log :\mathbb {R} ^{+}\to \mathbb {R}$ satisfies $\log(xy)=\log x+\log y$ for all $x,y\in \mathbb {R} ^{+},$ so it is a group homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The exponential function $\exp :\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{+}$ satisfies $\exp(x+y)=(\exp x)(\exp y)$ for all $x,y\in \mathbb {R} ,$ so it too is a homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The identities $\log \exp x=x$ and $\exp \log y=y$ show that $\log$ and $\exp$ are inverses of each other.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] So, $\exp :\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{+}\quad {\text{and}}\quad \log :\mathbb {R} ^{+}\to \mathbb {R}$ are group isomorphisms that are inverse of each other.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The $\log$ function is an isomorphism which translates multiplication of positive real numbers into addition of real numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] This facility makes it possible to multiply real numbers using a ruler and a table of logarithms, or using a slide rule with a logarithmic scale.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Consider the ring $\mathbb {Z} _{6}$ of the integers from 0 to 5 with addition and multiplication modulo 6.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Also consider the ring $\mathbb {Z} _{2}\times \mathbb {Z} _{3}$ of the ordered pairs where the first element is an integer modulo 2 and the second element is an integer modulo 3, with component-wise addition and multiplication modulo 2 and 3.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] This is a special case of the Chinese remainder theorem which asserts that, if ⁠ m ⁠ and ⁠ n ⁠ are coprime integers, the ring of the integers modulo ⁠ $mn$ ⁠ is isomorphic to the direct product of the integers modulo ⁠ m ⁠ and the integers modulo ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] S is reflexive, irreflexive, symmetric, antisymmetric, asymmetric, transitive, total, trichotomous, a partial order, total order, well-order, strict weak order, total preorder (weak order), an equivalence relation, or a relation with any other special properties, if and only if R is.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] If $X=Y,$ then this is a relation-preserving automorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In algebra, isomorphisms are defined for all algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Just as the automorphisms of an algebraic structure form a group, the isomorphisms between two algebras sharing a common structure form a heap.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Letting a particular isomorphism identify the two structures turns this heap into a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In mathematical analysis, the Laplace transform is an isomorphism mapping hard differential equations into easier algebraic equations.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In order theory, an isomorphism between two partially ordered sets *P* and *Q* is a bijective map f from *P* to *Q* that preserves the order structure in the sense that for any elements x and y of *P* we have x less than y in *P* if and only if $f(x)$ is less than $f(y)$ in *Q*.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] As an example, the set {1,2,3,6} of whole numbers ordered by the *is-a-factor-of* relation is isomorphic to the set {*O*, *A*, *B*, *AB*} of blood types ordered by the *can-donate-to* relation.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In mathematical analysis, an isomorphism between two Hilbert spaces is a bijection preserving addition, scalar multiplication, and inner product.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In early theories of logical atomism, the formal relationship between facts and true propositions was theorized by Bertrand Russell and Ludwig Wittgenstein to be isomorphic.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] An example of this line of thinking can be found in Russell's *Introduction to Mathematical Philosophy*.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In cybernetics, the good regulator theorem or Conant–Ashby theorem is stated as "Every good regulator of a system must be a model of that system".
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Whether regulated or self-regulating, an isomorphism is required between the regulator and processing parts of the system.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Two categories C and D are isomorphic if there exist functors $F:C\to D$ and $G:D\to C$ which are mutually inverse to each other, that is, $FG=1_{D}$ (the identity functor on D) and $GF=1_{C}$ (the identity functor on C).
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In algebraic categories (specifically, categories of varieties in the sense of universal algebra), an isomorphism is the same as a homomorphism which is bijective on underlying sets.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] However, there are concrete categories in which bijective morphisms are not necessarily isomorphisms (such as the category of topological spaces).
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Since a composition of isomorphisms is an isomorphism, the identity is an isomorphism, and the inverse of an isomorphism is an isomorphism, the relation that two mathematical objects are isomorphic is an equivalence relation.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] An equivalence class given by isomorphisms is commonly called an **isomorphism class**.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Examples of isomorphism classes are plentiful in mathematics.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] However, there are circumstances in which the isomorphism class of an object conceals vital information about it.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Although there are cases where isomorphic objects can be considered equal, one must distinguish *equality* and *isomorphism*.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Equality is when two objects are the same, and therefore everything that is true about one object is true about the other.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] On the other hand, isomorphisms are related to some structure, and two isomorphic objects share only the properties that are related to this structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] By contrast, the sets $\{4,5,6\}$ and $\{1,2,3\}$ are not *equal* since they do not have the same elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] and no one isomorphism is intrinsically better than any other.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Also, integers and even numbers are isomorphic as ordered sets and abelian groups (for addition), but cannot be considered equal sets, since one is a proper subset of the other.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] This is generally the case for objects defined by universal properties.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] For example, the polynomial rings ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} [X,Y]$ ⁠, ⁠ $(\mathbb {Z} [X])[Y]$ ⁠, and ⁠ $(\mathbb {Z} [Y])[X]$ ⁠ are considered as equal, since they all satisfy the same universal property.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] As another example, the ring localizations $R_{f}$ , $R_{f^{2}}$ , and $R[X]/(1-fX)$ are considered equal for the same reason.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] In these examples, the "equal" objects contain elements that are not set-theoretically identical, so they are not equal in this strict sense.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] However, because they are unique up to unique isomorphism, they can be canonically identified and treated as the same mathematical object.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] When objects defined by their properties are equated in this way, we can speak of them as unique entities (e.g., *the* Klein four-group or *the* complex numbers), even though two people may have different constructions or realizations in mind.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The rational numbers, for instance, are formally defined as equivalence classes of pairs of integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The universal property of the rational numbers is essentially that they form a field that contains the integers and does not contain any proper subfield.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] Given two fields with these properties, there is a unique field isomorphism between them.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] This allows identifying these two fields, since every property of one of them can be transferred to the other through the isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The real numbers that can be expressed as a quotient of integers form the smallest subfield of the reals.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] There is thus a unique isomorphism from this subfield of the reals to the rational numbers defined by equivalence classes.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] So, the rational numbers may be identified to the elements of a subset of the real numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] However, in some contexts this identification is not allowed.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] For example, in computer languages and type theory, real numbers and rational numbers have different representations, and the identification must be replaced with a type conversion.
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] The most common notation to denote that two objects *A* and *B* are isomorphic is $A\cong B$ , and if $f:A\to B$ maps *A* isomorphically to *B*, then one can also write $f:A\;{\overset {\sim }{\longrightarrow }}\;B$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/isomorphism] However, depending on context, some authors may also use symbols including $\simeq$ , or $\approx$ to denote an isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In mathematics, a **module** is a generalization of the notion of vector space in which the field of scalars is replaced by a (not necessarily commutative) ring.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] The concept of a *module* also generalizes the notion of an abelian group, since the abelian groups are exactly the modules over the ring of integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Like a vector space, a module is an additive abelian group, and scalar multiplication is distributive over the operations of addition between elements of the ring or module and is compatible with the ring multiplication.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Modules are very closely related to the representation theory of groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] They are also one of the central notions of commutative algebra and homological algebra, and are used widely in algebraic geometry and algebraic topology.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In a vector space, the set of scalars is a field and acts on the vectors by scalar multiplication, subject to certain axioms such as the distributive law.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In a module, the scalars need only be a ring, so the module concept represents a significant generalization.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In commutative algebra, both ideals and quotient rings are modules, so that many arguments about ideals or quotient rings can be combined into a single argument about modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In non-commutative algebra, the distinction between left ideals, ideals, and modules becomes more pronounced, though some ring-theoretic conditions can be expressed either about left ideals or left modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Much of the theory of modules consists of extending as many of the desirable properties of vector spaces as possible to the realm of modules over a "well-behaved" ring, such as a principal ideal domain.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Suppose that *R* is a ring, and 1 is its multiplicative identity.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] The operation · is called *scalar multiplication*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Often the symbol · is omitted, but in this article we use it and reserve juxtaposition for multiplication in *R*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] One may write *R**M* to emphasize that *M* is a left *R*-module.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] A **right *R*-module** *M**R* is defined similarly in terms of an operation · : *M* × *R* → *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] one gets a right-module, even if the scalars are written on the left.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] However, writing the scalars on the left for left-modules and on the right for right modules makes the manipulation of property 3 much easier.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Authors who do not require rings to be unital omit condition 4 in the definition above; they would call the structures defined above "unital left *R*-modules".
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In this article, consistent with the glossary of ring theory, all rings and modules are assumed to be unital.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] If *R* is commutative, then left *R*-modules are the same as right *R*-modules and are simply called *R*-modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Most often the scalars are written on the left in this case.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Suppose *M* is a left *R*-module and *N* is a subgroup of *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Then *N* is a **submodule** (or more explicitly an *R*-submodule) if for any *n* in *N* and any *r* in *R*, the product *r* ⋅ *n* (or *n* ⋅ *r* for a right *R*-module) is in *N*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] This, like any homomorphism of mathematical objects, is just a mapping that preserves the structure of the objects.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Another name for a homomorphism of *R*-modules is an *R*-linear map.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] A bijective module homomorphism *f* : *M* → *N* is called a module isomorphism, and the two modules *M* and *N* are called **isomorphic**.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Two isomorphic modules are identical for all practical purposes, differing solely in the notation for their elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] The kernel of a module homomorphism *f* : *M* → *N* is the submodule of *M* consisting of all elements that are sent to zero by *f*, and the image of *f* is the submodule of *N* consisting of values *f*(*m*) for all elements *m* of *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] The isomorphism theorems familiar from groups and vector spaces are also valid for *R*-modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Given a ring *R*, the set of all left *R*-modules together with their module homomorphisms forms an abelian category, denoted by *R*-**Mod** (see category of modules).
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] These are the modules that behave very much like vector spaces.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] of free modules and share many of their desirable properties.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] are defined dually to projective modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] is a direct sum (finite or not) of simple modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Every simple module is indecomposable, but there are indecomposable modules that are not simple (e.g.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] on submodules, that is, every increasing chain of submodules becomes stationary after finitely many steps.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Equivalently, every submodule is finitely generated.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] on submodules, that is, every decreasing chain of submodules becomes stationary after finitely many steps.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] is a module in which all pairs of nonzero submodules have nonzero intersection.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] A representation of a group *G* over a field *k* is a module over the group ring *k*[*G*].
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] If *M* is a left *R*-module, then the *action* of an element *r* in *R* is defined to be the map *M* → *M* that sends each *x* to *rx* (or *xr* in the case of a right module), and is necessarily a group endomorphism of the abelian group (*M*, +).
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] The set of all group endomorphisms of *M* is denoted End**Z**(*M*) and forms a ring under addition and composition, and sending a ring element *r* of *R* to its action actually defines a ring homomorphism from *R* to End**Z**(*M*).
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Such a ring homomorphism *R* → End**Z**(*M*) is called a *representation* of the abelian group *M* over the ring *R*; an alternative and equivalent way of defining left *R*-modules is to say that a left *R*-module is an abelian group *M* together with a representation of *M* over *R*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Such a representation *R* → End**Z**(*M*) may also be called a *ring action* of *R* on *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] A representation is called *faithful* if the map *R* → End**Z**(*M*) is injective.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In terms of modules, this means that if *r* is an element of *R* such that *rx* = 0 for all *x* in *M*, then *r* = 0.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Every abelian group is a faithful module over the integers or over the ring of integers modulo *n*, **Z**/*n***Z**, for some *n*.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] A ring *R* corresponds to a preadditive category **R** with a single object.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] With this understanding, a left *R*-module is just a covariant additive functor from **R** to the category of abelian groups **Ab**, and right *R*-modules are contravariant additive functors.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] This suggests that, if **C** is any preadditive category, a covariant additive functor from **C** to **Ab** should be considered a generalized left module over **C**.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] These functors form a functor category **C**-**Mod**, which is the natural generalization of the module category *R*-**Mod**.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Modules over *commutative* rings can be generalized in a different direction: take a ringed space (*X*, O*X*) and consider the sheaves of O*X*-modules (see sheaf of modules).
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] These form a category O*X*-**Mod**, and play an important role in modern algebraic geometry.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] If *X* has only a single point, then this is a module category in the old sense over the commutative ring O*X*(*X*).
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] One can also consider modules over a semiring, called a semimodule.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Modules over rings are abelian groups, but modules over semirings are only commutative monoids.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Most applications of modules are still possible.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] In particular, for any semiring *S*, the matrices over *S* form a semiring over which the tuples of elements from *S* are a module (in this generalized sense only).
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] This allows a further generalization of the concept of vector space incorporating the semirings from theoretical computer science.
[src:abstract-algebra/module-mathematics] Over near-rings, one can consider near-ring modules, a nonabelian generalization of modules.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In abstract algebra, a **monoid** is a set equipped with an associative binary operation and an identity element.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For example, the natural numbers with addition form a monoid, the identity element being 0.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Such algebraic structures occur in several branches of mathematics.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The functions from a set into itself form a monoid with respect to function composition.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] More generally, in category theory, the morphisms of an object to itself form a monoid, and, conversely, a monoid may be viewed as a category with a single object.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In computer science and computer programming, the set of strings built from a given set of characters is a free monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Transition monoids and syntactic monoids are used in describing finite-state machines.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Trace monoids and history monoids provide a foundation for process calculi and concurrent computing.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In theoretical computer science, the study of monoids is fundamental for automata theory (Krohn–Rhodes theory), and formal language theory (star height problem).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] See semigroup for the history of the subject, and some other general properties of monoids.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In other words, a monoid is a semigroup with an identity element.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] It can also be thought of as a magma with associativity and identity.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The identity element of a monoid is unique.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For this reason the identity is regarded as a constant, i. e.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The monoid therefore is characterized by specification of the triple (*S*, • , *e*).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Depending on the context, the symbol for the binary operation may be omitted, so that the operation is denoted by juxtaposition; for example, the monoid axioms may be written (*ab*)*c* = *a*(*bc*) and *ea* = *ae* = *a*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] This notation does not imply that it is numbers being multiplied.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A group is a special case of a monoid where every element has an inverse.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A **submonoid** of a monoid (*M*, •) is a subset *N* of *M* that is closed under the monoid operation and contains the identity element *e* of *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In this case, *N* is a monoid under the binary operation inherited from *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] On the other hand, if *N* is a subset of a monoid that is closed under the monoid operation, and is a monoid for this inherited operation, then *N* is not always a submonoid, since the identity elements may differ.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For example, the singleton set {0} is closed under multiplication, and is not a submonoid of the (multiplicative) monoid of the nonnegative integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A subset *S* of *M* is said to *generate* *M* if the smallest submonoid of *M* containing *S* is *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] If there is a finite set that generates *M*, then *M* is said to be a **finitely generated monoid**.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A monoid whose operation is commutative is called a **commutative monoid** (or, less commonly, an **abelian monoid**).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Commutative monoids are often written additively.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Any commutative monoid is endowed with its *algebraic* preordering ≤, defined by *x* ≤ *y* if there exists *z* such that *x* + *z* = *y*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] An *order-unit* of a commutative monoid *M* is an element *u* of *M* such that for any element *x* of *M*, there exists *v* in the set generated by *u* such that *x* ≤ *v*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] This is often used in case *M* is the positive cone of a partially ordered abelian group *G*, in which case we say that *u* is an order-unit of *G*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A monoid for which the operation is commutative for some, but not all elements is a trace monoid; trace monoids commonly occur in the theory of concurrent computation.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Multiplication of elements in ⟨*f*⟩ is then given by function composition.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] When *k* = 0 then the function *f* is a permutation of {0, 1, 2, ..., *n*−1}, and gives the unique cyclic group of order *n*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] By the monoid axioms the identity element *e* is unique, since if *e* and *f* were identity elements of a monoid, then *e* = *ef* = *f*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For each nonnegative integer *n*, one can define the product $p_{n}=\textstyle \prod _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}$ of any sequence (*a*1, ..., *a**n*) of *n* elements of a monoid recursively: let *p*0 = *e* and let *p**m* = *p**m*−1 • *a**m* for 1 ≤ *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] As a special case, one can define nonnegative integer powers of an element *x* of a monoid: *x*0 = 1 and *x**n* = *x**n*−1 • *x* for *n* ≥ 1.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] An element *x* is called invertible if there exists an element *y* such that *x* • *y* = *e* and *y* • *x* = *e*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The element *y* is called the inverse of *x*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Inverses, if they exist, are unique: if *y* and *z* are inverses of *x*, then by associativity *y* = *ey* = (*zx*)*y* = *z*(*xy*) = *ze* = *z*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] If *x* is invertible, say with inverse *y*, then one can define negative powers of *x* by setting *x*−*n* = *y**n* for each *n* ≥ 1; this makes the equation *x**m*+*n* = *x**m* • *x**n* hold for all *m*, *n* ∈ **Z**.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The set of all invertible elements in a monoid, together with the operation •, forms a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A monoid (*M*, •) has the cancellation property (or is cancellative) if for all *a*, *b* and *c* in *M*, the equality *a* • *b* = *a* • *c* implies *b* = *c*, and the equality *b* • *a* = *c* • *a* implies *b* = *c*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A commutative monoid with the cancellation property can always be embedded in a group via the *Grothendieck group construction*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] That is how the additive group of the integers (a group with operation +) is constructed from the additive monoid of natural numbers (a commutative monoid with operation + and cancellation property).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] However, a non-commutative cancellative monoid need not be embeddable in a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] If a monoid has the cancellation property and is *finite*, then it is in fact a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The right- and left-cancellative elements of a monoid each in turn form a submonoid (i.e. are closed under the operation and obviously include the identity).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] This means that the cancellative elements of any commutative monoid can be extended to a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The cancellative property in a monoid is not necessary to perform the Grothendieck construction – commutativity is sufficient.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] However, if a commutative monoid does not have the cancellation property, the homomorphism of the monoid into its Grothendieck group is not injective.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] More precisely, if *a* • *b* = *a* • *c*, then *b* and *c* have the same image in the Grothendieck group, even if *b* ≠ *c*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In particular, if the monoid has an absorbing element, then its Grothendieck group is the trivial group.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] If an inverse monoid is cancellative, then it is a group.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In the opposite direction, a *zerosumfree monoid* is an additively written monoid in which *a* + *b* = 0 implies that *a* = 0 and *b* = 0: equivalently, that no element other than zero has an additive inverse.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Let *M* be a monoid, with the binary operation denoted by • and the identity element denoted by *e*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] This is the analogue in monoid theory of a (left) group action.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Right *M*-acts are defined in a similar way.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A monoid with an act is also known as an *operator monoid*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Important examples include transition systems of semiautomata.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A transformation semigroup can be made into an operator monoid by adjoining the identity transformation.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] where *e**M* and *e**N* are the identities on *M* and *N* respectively.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Monoid homomorphisms are sometimes simply called **monoid morphisms**.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Not every semigroup homomorphism between monoids is a monoid homomorphism, since it may not map the identity to the identity of the target monoid, even though the identity is the identity of the image of the homomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For example, consider [**Z**]*n*, the set of residue classes modulo *n* equipped with multiplication.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In particular, [1]*n* is the identity element.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] However, *f*([1]3) = [3]6 ≠ [1]6, so a monoid homomorphism is a semigroup homomorphism between monoids that maps the identity of the first monoid to the identity of the second monoid and the latter condition cannot be omitted.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In contrast, a semigroup homomorphism between groups is always a group homomorphism, as it necessarily preserves the identity (because, in the target group of the homomorphism, the identity element is the only element *x* such that *x* ⋅ *x* = *x*).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A bijective monoid homomorphism is called a monoid isomorphism.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Two monoids are said to be isomorphic if there is a monoid isomorphism between them.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Monoids may be given a *presentation*, much in the same way that groups can be specified by means of a group presentation.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] One does this by specifying a set of generators Σ, and a set of relations on the free monoid Σ∗.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] One does this by extending (finite) binary relations on Σ∗ to monoid congruences, and then constructing the quotient monoid, as above.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Given a binary relation *R* ⊂ Σ∗ × Σ∗, one defines its symmetric closure as *R* ∪ *R*−1.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] This can be extended to a symmetric relation *E* ⊂ Σ∗ × Σ∗ by defining *x* ~*E* *y* if and only if *x* = *sut* and *y* = *svt* for some strings *u*, *v*, *s*, *t* ∈ Σ∗ with (*u*,*v*) ∈ *R* ∪ *R*−1.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Finally, one takes the reflexive and transitive closure of *E*, which is then a monoid congruence.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In the typical situation, the relation *R* is simply given as a set of equations, so that *R* = {*u*1 = *v*1, ..., *u**n* = *v**n*}.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] is the plactic monoid of degree 2 (it has infinite order).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Elements of this plactic monoid may be written as $a^{i}b^{j}(ba)^{k}$ for integers *i*, *j*, *k*, as the relations show that *ba* commutes with both *a* and *b*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Monoids can be viewed as a special class of categories.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Indeed, the axioms required of a monoid operation are exactly those required of morphism composition when restricted to the set of all morphisms whose source and target is a given object.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A monoid is, essentially, the same thing as a category with a single object.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] More precisely, given a monoid (*M*, •), one can construct a small category with only one object and whose morphisms are the elements of *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The composition of morphisms is given by the monoid operation •.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Likewise, monoid homomorphisms are just functors between single object categories.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] So this construction gives an equivalence between the category of (small) monoids **Mon** and a full subcategory of the category of (small) categories **Cat**.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Similarly, the category of groups is equivalent to another full subcategory of **Cat**.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In this sense, category theory can be thought of as an extension of the concept of a monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Many definitions and theorems about monoids can be generalised to small categories with more than one object.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For example, a quotient of a category with one object is just a quotient monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Monoids, just like other algebraic structures, also form their own category, **Mon**, whose objects are monoids and whose morphisms are monoid homomorphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] There is also a notion of monoid object which is an abstract definition of what is a monoid in a category.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A monoid object in **Set** is just a monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In computer science, many abstract data types can be endowed with a monoid structure.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In a common pattern, a sequence of elements of a monoid is "folded" or "accumulated" to produce a final value.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For instance, many iterative algorithms need to update some kind of "running total" at each iteration; this pattern may be elegantly expressed by a monoid operation.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Alternatively, the associativity of monoid operations ensures that the operation can be parallelized by employing a prefix sum or similar algorithm, in order to utilize multiple cores or processors efficiently.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] In addition, any data structure can be 'folded' in a similar way, given a serialization of its elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For instance, the result of "folding" a binary tree might differ depending on pre-order vs. post-order tree traversal.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] An application of monoids in computer science is the so-called MapReduce programming model (see Encoding Map-Reduce As A Monoid With Left Folding).
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] MapReduce, in computing, consists of two or three operations.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] Given a dataset, "Map" consists of mapping arbitrary data to elements of a specific monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] "Reduce" consists of folding those elements, so that in the end we produce just one element.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] For example, if we have a multiset, in a program it is represented as a map from elements to their numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] The number of distinct keys may be too big, and in this case, the multiset is being sharded.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] To finalize reduction properly, the "Shuffling" stage regroups the data among the nodes.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] If we do not need this step, the whole Map/Reduce consists of mapping and reducing; both operations are parallelizable, the former due to its element-wise nature, the latter due to associativity of the monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] An **ordered commutative monoid** is a commutative monoid *M* together with a partial ordering ≤ such that *a* ≥ 0 for every *a* ∈ *M*, and *a* ≤ *b* implies *a* + *c* ≤ *b* + *c* for all *a*, *b*, *c* ∈ *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] A **continuous monoid** is an ordered commutative monoid (*M*, ≤) in which every directed subset has a least upper bound, and these least upper bounds are compatible with the monoid operation: $a+\sup S=\sup(a+S)$ for every *a* ∈ *M* and directed subset *S* of *M*.
[src:abstract-algebra/monoid] If (*M*, ≤) is a continuous monoid, then for any index set *I* and collection of elements (*a**i*)*i*∈*I*, one can define $\sum _{I}a_{i}=\sup _{{\text{finite }}E\subset I}\;\sum _{E}a_{i},$ and *M* together with this infinitary sum operation is a complete monoid.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] In the branch of mathematics known as group theory, a **quotient group** or **factor group** is a group obtained by aggregating similar elements of a larger group using an equivalence relation that preserves some of the group structure (the rest of the structure is "factored out").
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] For example, the cyclic group of addition modulo *n* can be obtained from the group of integers under addition by identifying elements that differ by a multiple of n and defining a group structure that operates on each such class (known as a congruence class) as a single entity.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] For a congruence relation on a group, the equivalence class of the identity element is always a normal subgroup of the original group, and the other equivalence classes are precisely the cosets of that normal subgroup.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The resulting quotient is written ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠, where G is the original group and N is the normal subgroup.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This is read as '⁠ $G{\bmod {N}}$ ⁠', where ${\text{mod}}$ is short for modulo.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] (The notation ⁠ $G\,/\,H$ ⁠ should be interpreted with caution, as some authors (e.g., Vinberg) use it to represent the left cosets of H in G for *any* subgroup H , even though these cosets do not form a group if H is not normal in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Much of the importance of quotient groups is derived from their relation to homomorphisms.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The first isomorphism theorem states that the image of any group G under a homomorphism is always isomorphic to a quotient of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Specifically, the image of G under a homomorphism $\varphi :G\rightarrow H$ is isomorphic to $G\,/\,\ker(\varphi )$ where $\ker(\varphi )$ denotes the kernel of ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The dual notion of a quotient group is a subgroup, these being the two primary ways of forming a smaller group from a larger one.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Any normal subgroup has a corresponding quotient group, formed from the larger group by eliminating the distinction between elements of the subgroup.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] In category theory, quotient groups are examples of quotient objects, which are dual to subobjects.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Given a group G and a subgroup ⁠ H ⁠, and a fixed element $a\in G$ , one can consider the corresponding left coset: ⁠ $aH:=\left\{ah:h\in H\right\}$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Cosets are a natural class of subsets of a group; for example consider the abelian group G of integers, with operation defined by the usual addition, and the subgroup H of even integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Then there are exactly two cosets: ⁠ $0+H$ ⁠, which are the even integers, and ⁠ $1+H$ ⁠, which are the odd integers (here we are using additive notation for the binary operation instead of multiplicative notation).
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient group $G/H$ is thus $\{0+H,1+H\}$ , a two-element group isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /2\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] For a general subgroup ⁠ H ⁠, it is desirable to define a compatible group operation on the set of all possible cosets, ⁠ $\left\{aH:a\in G\right\}$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This is possible exactly when H is a normal subgroup, see below.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] A subgroup N of a group G is normal if and only if the coset equality $aN=Na$ holds for all ⁠ $a\in G$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] A normal subgroup of G is denoted ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Let N be a normal subgroup of a group ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient group $G\,/\,N$ is defined to be the set of all left cosets of N in ⁠ G ⁠, i.e. ⁠ $G\,/\,N=\left\{aN:a\in G\right\}$ ⁠, with the group operation defined as ⁠ $(aN)(bN)=(ab)N\ \forall \ a,b\in G$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] It can be shown that this operation satisfies all of the group axioms.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] As N is a normal subgroup of G , the left and right cosets of N in G are the same, and so $G\,/\,N$ could equivalently have been defined to be the set of all right cosets of N in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Since the identity element ⁠ $e\in N$ ⁠, ⁠ $a\in aN$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] To avoid contradiction, this definition requires that $(ab)N$ is the same when $aN$ or $bN$ are constructed using different elements of G , i.e. if ⁠ $aN=xN$ ⁠ and ⁠ $bN=yN$ ⁠, then ⁠ $(ab)N=(xy)N$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This can be shown to always be true when N is a normal subgroup as follows: ${\textstyle (ab)N=a(bN)=a(yN)=a(Ny)=(aN)y=(xN)y=x(Ny)=x(yN)=(xy)N.}$ where ⁠ $a,b,x,y\in G$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This proof is only valid for normal subgroups, as it uses the property ⁠ $yN=Ny$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This shows that the operation is well-defined when N is a normal subgroup.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The definition however *required* that N be a normal subgroup.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This is because the group operation is *only* well-defined for normal subgroups.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] To show this, first assume that the group operation is well defined, i.e. that if $xN=aN$ and $yN=bN$ for any ⁠ $x,y,a,b\in G$ ⁠, then ⁠ $(ab)N=(xy)N$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Using $gN=(ng)N$ , we have ⁠ $N=(g^{-1}ng)N$ ⁠, and so ⁠ $g^{-1}ng\in N,\;\forall \,n\in N,g\in G$ ⁠, meaning that N must be a normal subgroup of G .
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] As such, the group operation is only well-defined if N is a normal subgroup.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Consider the subgroup ⁠ $N=\left\{0,3\right\}$ ⁠, which is normal because G is abelian.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The binary operation defined above makes this set into a group, known as the quotient group, which in this case is isomorphic to the cyclic group of order 3.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient group $G\,/\,N$ can be compared to division of integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] When dividing 12 by 3 one obtains the result 4 because one can regroup 12 objects into 4 subcollections of 3 objects.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient group is the same idea, although one ends up with a group for a final answer instead of a number.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] In general groups have more structure than an arbitrary collection of objects: in the quotient ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠, therefore the group structure is used to form a natural "regrouping".
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Because we started with a group and normal subgroup, the final quotient contains more information than just the number of cosets (which is what regular division yields), but instead has a group structure itself.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Consider the group of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ (under addition) and the subgroup $2\mathbb {Z}$ consisting of all even integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This is a normal subgroup, because $\mathbb {Z}$ is abelian.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] There are only two cosets: the set of even integers and the set of odd integers, and therefore the quotient group $\mathbb {Z} \,/\,2\mathbb {Z}$ is the cyclic group with two elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This quotient group is isomorphic with the set $\left\{0,1\right\}$ with addition modulo 2; informally, it is sometimes said that $\mathbb {Z} \,/\,2\mathbb {Z}$ *equals* the set $\left\{0,1\right\}$ with addition modulo 2.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] A slight generalization of the last example.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Once again consider the group of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ under addition.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] We will consider the subgroup $n\mathbb {Z}$ of $\mathbb {Z}$ consisting of all multiples of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Once again $n\mathbb {Z}$ is normal in $\mathbb {Z}$ because $\mathbb {Z}$ is abelian.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] An integer k belongs to the coset ⁠ $r+n\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, where r is the remainder when dividing k by ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient $\mathbb {Z} \,/\,n\mathbb {Z}$ can be thought of as the group of "remainders" modulo ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The twelfth roots of unity, which are points on the complex unit circle, form a multiplicative abelian group ⁠ G ⁠, shown on the picture on the right as colored balls with the number at each point giving its complex argument.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Consider its subgroup N made of the fourth roots of unity, shown as red balls.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This normal subgroup splits the group into three cosets, shown in red, green and blue.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] One can check that the cosets form a group of three elements (the product of a red element with a blue element is blue, the inverse of a blue element is green, etc.).
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Thus, the quotient group $G\,/\,N$ is the group of three colors, which turns out to be the cyclic group with three elements.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Consider the group of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ under addition, and the subgroup $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Each coset of $\mathbb {Z}$ in $\mathbb {R}$ is a set of the form ⁠ $a+\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠, where a is a real number.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Since $a_{1}+\mathbb {Z}$ and $a_{2}+\mathbb {Z}$ are identical sets when the non-integer parts of $a_{1}$ and $a_{2}$ are equal, one may impose the restriction $0\leq a<1$ without change of meaning.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Adding such cosets is done by adding the corresponding real numbers, and subtracting 1 if the result is greater than or equal to 1.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient group $\mathbb {R} \,/\,\mathbb {Z}$ is isomorphic to the circle group, the group of complex numbers of absolute value 1 under multiplication, or correspondingly, the group of rotations in 2D about the origin, that is, the special orthogonal group ⁠ $\mathrm {SO} (2)$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] An isomorphism is given by $f(a+\mathbb {Z} )=\exp(2\pi ia)$ (see Euler's identity).
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] If G is the group of invertible $3\times 3$ real matrices, and N is the subgroup of $3\times 3$ real matrices with determinant 1, then N is normal in G (since it is the kernel of the determinant homomorphism).
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The cosets of N are the sets of matrices with a given determinant, and hence $G\,/\,N$ is isomorphic to the multiplicative group of non-zero real numbers.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The group N is known as the special linear group ⁠ $\mathrm {SL} (3)$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The set N of ⁠ n ⁠th residues is a multiplicative subgroup isomorphic to ⁠ $(\mathbb {Z} _{n})^{\times }$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The Paillier cryptosystem is based on the conjecture that it is difficult to determine the coset of a random element of G without knowing the factorization of ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The quotient group $G\,/\,G$ is isomorphic to the trivial group (the group with one element), and $G\,/\,\left\{e\right\}$ is isomorphic to ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The order of ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠, by definition the number of elements, is equal to ⁠ $\vert G:N\vert$ ⁠, the index of N in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] If G is finite, the index is also equal to the order of G divided by the order of ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The set $G\,/\,N$ may be finite, although both G and N are infinite (for example, ⁠ $\mathbb {Z} \,/\,2\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠).
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] There is a "natural" surjective group homomorphism ⁠ $\pi :G\rightarrow G\,/\,N$ ⁠, sending each element g of G to the coset of N to which g belongs, that is: ⁠ $\pi (g)=gN$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The mapping $\pi$ is sometimes called the *canonical projection of G onto ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠*.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] There is a bijective correspondence between the subgroups of G that contain N and the subgroups of ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠; if H is a subgroup of G containing ⁠ N ⁠, then the corresponding subgroup of $G\,/\,N$ is ⁠ $\pi (H)$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This correspondence holds for normal subgroups of G and $G\,/\,N$ as well, and is formalized in the lattice theorem.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Several important properties of quotient groups are recorded in the fundamental theorem on homomorphisms and the isomorphism theorems.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] If G is abelian, nilpotent, solvable, cyclic or finitely generated, then so is ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] If H is a subgroup in a finite group ⁠ G ⁠, and the order of H is one half of the order of ⁠ G ⁠, then H is guaranteed to be a normal subgroup, so $G\,/\,H$ exists and is isomorphic to ⁠ $\mathrm {C} _{2}$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This result can also be stated as "any subgroup of index 2 is normal", and in this form it applies also to infinite groups.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Furthermore, if p is the smallest prime number dividing the order of a finite group, ⁠ G ⁠, then if $G\,/\,H$ has order ⁠ p ⁠, H must be a normal subgroup of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Given G and a normal subgroup ⁠ N ⁠, then G is a group extension of $G\,/\,N$ by ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] One could ask whether this extension is trivial or split; in other words, one could ask whether G is a direct product or semidirect product of N and ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] This is a special case of the extension problem.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] But $\mathrm {Z} _{2}$ has only the trivial automorphism, so the only semi-direct product of N and $G\,/\,N$ is the direct product.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Since $\mathrm {Z} _{4}$ is different from ⁠ $\mathrm {Z} _{2}\times \mathrm {Z} _{2}$ ⁠, we conclude that G is not a semi-direct product of N and ⁠ $G\,/\,N$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] If G is a Lie group and N is a normal and (topologically) closed Lie subgroup of ⁠ G ⁠, the quotient $G\,/\,N$ is also a Lie group.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] In this case, the original group *G* has the structure of a fiber bundle (specifically, a principal ⁠ N ⁠-bundle), with base space $G\,/\,N$ and fiber ⁠ N ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The dimension of $G\,/\,N$ equals ⁠ $\dim G-\dim N$ ⁠.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Note that the condition that N is closed is necessary.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] Indeed, if N is not closed then the quotient space is not a T1-space (since there is a coset in the quotient which cannot be separated from the identity by an open set), and thus not a Hausdorff space.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] For a non-normal Lie subgroup ⁠ N ⁠, the space $G\,/\,N$ of left cosets is not a group, but simply a differentiable manifold on which G acts.
[src:abstract-algebra/quotient-group] The result is known as a homogeneous space.
